  "text": "We tested mice in an automated TSC fear conditioning system v8.06 (TSE systems GmbH, Germany). On the first day, mice were placed in an illuminated chamber with transparent walls and metal grid floor (context A). After 120 s of acclimation period, 5 pairings of conditioned stimulus (CS) were provided (30 s, 80db, white noise), followed by unconditioned stimulus (UCS) (0.7 mA foot shock for 2 s). Inter-pairing intervals varied with an average of 60 s (30-120 s). 120 s of consolidation period was allowed. On the next day, mice were returned to context A and freezing behavior was assessed for three minutes, without CS or UCS. During day three, mice were placed in a novel dark opaque chamber with wooden floor (context B). One CS, not followed by the UCS, was provided after 120 s acclimation period and mice were observed for three minutes. This was followed by a series of 14 CS without UCS, with 15 s interval between the stimuli. After this cue extinction procedure, 120 s of consolidation was allowed. On the 4th day, mice were returned to context B. After 120 s of acclimation period, one CS was provided, not followed by the UCS, and mice were observed for extinction retrieval behaviors for 5 min. The principal index of learning was freezing behavior defined by the absence of any visible movements except those required for respiration [CITATION_1] and was scored by TSC FCS v8.06 software.",
